        "excerpt": "When the prophets, Haggai the prophet and Zechariah the son of Iddo, prophesied to the Jews who were in Judah and Jerusalem in the name of the God of Israel, who was over them...",
        "body": "The opening verse names the chapter's causal force before it names anything else. It is not a new Persian edict, not a change in political climate, not renewed community resolve that restarts the construction. It is prophetic word. Haggai and Zechariah appear here without introduction because the original reader knew them: their canonical books supply the full content of what they preached. Haggai's opening oracle (Haggai 1:2-11) directly confronts the community's prioritization of their own houses over God's house — the precise stall Ezra 4 describes. Zechariah's opening call to repentance (Zechariah 1:2-6) names the same pattern: the fathers did not listen, and they suffered for it. The community in Ezra 5 is being called back from repeating the fathers' failure.\n\nThe phrase 'in the name of the God of Israel, who was over them' is the verse's theological weight-bearing clause. The 'name' invokes covenantal authorization — the prophets are not speaking from personal opinion or political analysis but from divine commissioning. 'Who was over them' has been variously rendered (the phrase is elliptical in Aramaic), but the most natural reading is that God 'was over them' — over the Jewish community — as their authoritative Lord, even in the years of silence. The prophets speak; the builders arise. The causation is unambiguous and immediate.\n\nZerubbabel and Jeshua represent the civil and priestly leadership respectively — the same pair who led the altar-building in Ezra 3:2 and who appear together again in Nehemiah 12:1 and Haggai 1:1. Their arising is not individual heroism; it is representative response. The 'prophets of God were with them supporting them' — the Hebrew-Aramaic sead ('supporting, strengthening') indicates ongoing accompaniment, not a one-time word. The prophets do not just ignite the work; they sustain it.\n\n> **Aramaic note.** *Nevah* (prophesied, v.1) is the Aramaic cognate of Hebrew *naba* — to bubble up, to speak under divine inspiration. *Sead* (supporting, v.2) means to prop up, to strengthen — the same verb used in Chronicles for those who strengthened the king's hand. The prophets are the structural support of the building project, not merely its catalysts."
